{"messages": [{"role": "system", "content": "You are an expert Manim Community Edition (CE) programmer. Generate clean, executable Manim CE Python code that creates mathematical animations. Always use 'from manim import *' and ensure all code is compatible with the latest Manim CE version. Return ONLY the Python code, no explanations."}, {"role": "user", "content": "Generate accurate and correct ManimCE Python code for the animation requested by the user. Here is the user's request: I would like to see an animated explanation of how to calculate the definite integral of x^3 from 0 to 2, with each step of the process displayed, including the use of the power rule for integration, the evaluation of the integral at the boundaries, and the final simplified answer. Can you also make sure to pause briefly after each new piece of information is shown so I can understand it fully before moving on?"}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "\\n from manim import *\n\nclass PendulumMotion(Scene):\n    def construct(self):\n        pivot = Dot(UP * 2)\n        bob = Dot(DOWN * 1)\n        rod = Line(pivot.get_center(), bob.get_center()).set_stroke(width=2)\n        pendulum = VGroup(pivot, rod, bob)\n        \n        self.play(FadeIn(pivot), GrowFromCenter(bob), ShowCreation(rod))\n        self.play(Rotating(rod, radians=PI/4, about_point=pivot.get_center(), rate_func=there_and_back, run_time=2))\n        self.wait(1) </s>"}]}
{"messages": [{"role": "system", "content": "You are an expert Manim Community Edition (CE) programmer. Generate clean, executable Manim CE Python code that creates mathematical animations. Always use 'from manim import *' and ensure all code is compatible with the latest Manim CE version. Return ONLY the Python code, no explanations."}, {"role": "user", "content": "Generate accurate and correct ManimCE Python code for the animation requested by the user. Here is the user's request: I would like to create an educational animation where different shapes appear one after another. First, I want a blue circle to grow from the center on the left side of the screen. Then, a green rectangle should fade in next to the blue circle on the right. Lastly, a red ellipse should grow from the top edge and appear next to the rectangle. Please make sure that each shape is clearly distinct and has some space between them. Can you also ensure that the animation pauses for a short while after the shapes appear so that the viewers can see the final result clearly?"}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "\\n from manim import *\n\nclass TripleIntegralExample(Scene):\n    def construct(self):\n        # Displaying the problem\n        problem = MathTex(r\"\\int_{0}^{1} \\int_{0}^{1} \\int_{0}^{1} xyz \\,dx\\,dy\\,dz\")\n        self.play(Write(problem))\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Explanation for innermost integral\n        explanation1 = Text(\"First, integrate with respect to x\", font_size=24).to_edge(UP)\n        self.play(Write(explanation1))\n        self.wait(2)\n\n        # Innermost integral result\n        x_integral_result = MathTex(r\"= \\int_{0}^{1} \\int_{0}^{1} [\\frac{1}{2}x^2yz]_{0}^{1} \\,dy\\,dz\")\n        self.play(ReplacementTransform(problem.copy(), x_integral_result))\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Explanation for middle integral\n        explanation2 = Text(\"Next, integrate with respect to y\", font_size=24).to_edge(UP)\n        self.play(Transform(explanation1, explanation2))\n        self.wait(2)\n\n        # Middle integral result\n        y_integral_result = MathTex(r\"= \\int_{0}^{1} [\\frac{1}{2}y^2z]_{0}^{1} \\,dz\")\n        self.play(ReplacementTransform(x_integral_result, y_integral_result))\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Explanation for the outermost integral\n        explanation3 = Text(\"Finally, integrate with respect to z\", font_size=24).to_edge(UP)\n        self.play(Transform(explanation1, explanation3))\n        self.wait(2)\n\n        # Outermost integral step and final solution\n        final_solution = MathTex(r\"= [\\frac{1}{2}z^2]_{0}^{1}\", r\"= \\frac{1}{2}\")\n        self.play(ReplacementTransform(y_integral_result, final_solution))\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Conclusion with result\n        self.clear()\n        self.wait(1)\n        self.play(Write(Text(\"The result of the triple integral is:\", font_size=24).to_edge(UP)))\n        self.play(Write(final_solution))\n        self.wait(1) </s>"}]}
{"messages": [{"role": "system", "content": "You are an expert Manim Community Edition (CE) programmer. Generate clean, executable Manim CE Python code that creates mathematical animations. Always use 'from manim import *' and ensure all code is compatible with the latest Manim CE version. Return ONLY the Python code, no explanations."}, {"role": "user", "content": "Generate accurate and correct ManimCE Python code for the animation requested by the user. Here is the user's request: Can you create an animated video using ManimCE that explains how to solve a first-order ordinary differential equation (ODE) using an integrating factor? I would like the video to include: \n\n1. The initial display of the ODE: dy/dx + 3y = x.\n2. A description and display of the integrating factor: mu(x) = e^(3x).\n3. The equation being multiplied by the integrating factor resulting in: e^(3x)*dy/dx + 3e^(3x)*y = xe^(3x).\n4. An announcement that we're looking at the general solution before integration, without actually displaying the integration step.\n5. The general solution after the integration of both sides: y(x) = (e^(-3x)/3)∫xe^(3x)dx + Ce^(-3x).\n6. The final general solution presented neatly: y = (1/3)x - (1/9) + Ce^(-3x).\n7. Then conclude by stating that we have solved the ODE and display the final solution again after clearing all previous writing off the screen. \n\nPlease ensure the transitions are smooth and allow for moments where the viewer can take in the information before moving on to the next step."}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "\\n from manim import *\n\nclass DiceRollSimulation(Scene):\n    def construct(self):\n        die_face = 0\n        roll_counts = [0] * 6  # List to hold counts of each face\n        roll_count_text = [\n            always_redraw(lambda i=i: Text(f\"{roll_counts[i]}\").next_to(die_face_mob, DOWN).shift(RIGHT * (i - 2.5) * 0.6))\n            for i in range(6)\n        ]\n\n        die_face_mob = Square(side_length=1)\n        die_face_label = always_redraw(lambda: Text(str(die_face)).move_to(die_face_mob.get_center()))\n        die_face_group = VGroup(die_face_mob, die_face_label)\n\n        self.add(die_face_group)\n        self.add(*roll_count_text)\n\n        for i in range(6):\n            self.play(FadeIn(roll_count_text[i]))\n\n        for _ in range(100):\n            die_face = random.randint(1, 6)\n            roll_counts[die_face - 1] += 1\n            self.play(\n                Transform(die_face_label, Text(str(die_face)).move_to(die_face_mob.get_center())),\n                run_time=0.1\n            )\n\n        self.wait(1) </s>"}]}
{"messages": [{"role": "system", "content": "You are an expert Manim Community Edition (CE) programmer. Generate clean, executable Manim CE Python code that creates mathematical animations. Always use 'from manim import *' and ensure all code is compatible with the latest Manim CE version. Return ONLY the Python code, no explanations."}, {"role": "user", "content": "Generate accurate and correct ManimCE Python code for the animation requested by the user. Here is the user's request: Can you create an animation where a piece of text saying \"tom marvolo riddle\" transitions into \"lord voldemort\" with a sweeping motion, and before this transformation, another text reading \"TransformMatchingShapes\" moves upwards on the screen? Additionally, the initial text \"tom marvolo riddle\" should appear through a writing animation, and after the transformation, both texts disappear from the screen."}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "\\n from manim import *\n\nconfig.frame_size = 1080, 1920 \nconfig.frame_width = 9\nconfig.frame_height = 16\n\nBACKGROUND_COLOR = \"#faf4e1\"\nTEXT_COLOR = \"#434343\"\nLIGHT_RED_COLOR = \"#f55e61\"\nLIGHT_GREEN_COLOR = \"#5fcb50\"\nLIGHT_BLUE_COLOR = \"#408ef5\"\nLIGHT_ORANGE_COLOR = \"#e3883d\"\nLIGHT_PURPLE_COLOR = \"#a346eb\"\nLIGHT_YELLOW_COLOR = \"#f9e24c\"\nAQUA_BLUE_COLOR = \"#16b0b5\"\nAQUA_GREEN_COLOR = \"#0dc786\"\nGREEN_COLOR = \"#34a853\"\nORANGE_COLOR = \"#fc5922\"\nDARK_RED_COLOR = \"#bf2626\"\nDARK_BLUE_COLOR = \"#3333FF\"\nDARK_PURPLE_COLOR = \"#5157b9\"\nSAND_COLOR = \"#b3a77d\"\nBROWN_COLOR = \"#b85842\"\n\ndef MathOperation(path, expression_text):\n    image = ImageMobject(path)\n    expression = Tex(expression_text, color=BLACK)\n    expression.scale(1.8)\n    group = Group(image, expression)\n    group.arrange(RIGHT, buff=0.25)\n\n    return group\n\ndef LetterOperation(expression, expression_result):\n    inner_group = Group(\n        Tex(expression, color=TEXT_COLOR).scale(1.8),\n        Tex(expression_result, color=TEXT_COLOR).scale(1.8),\n    ).arrange(DOWN, buff=0.8)\n    box = DashedVMobject(\n        SurroundingRectangle(inner_group, color=AQUA_BLUE_COLOR, buff=0.5),\n        num_dashes=25,\n        dashed_ratio=0.7\n    )\n    outer_group = Group(\n        box,\n        inner_group\n    )\n\n    return outer_group\n\nclass AlgebraWithLetters(Scene):\n    def construct(self):\n        self.camera.background_color = BACKGROUND_COLOR\n\n        operation_1 = LetterOperation(\"x + 3 = 5\", \"x = 2\")\n        operation_2 = LetterOperation(\"9 - d = 2\", \"d = 7\")\n        operation_3 = LetterOperation(\"2 . a = 6\", \"a = 3\")\n        Group(\n            operation_1, \n            operation_2, \n            operation_3\n        ).arrange(DOWN, buff=1)\n        \n        self.play(SpinInFromNothing(operation_1), run_time=0.7)\n        self.wait(3)\n        self.play(SpinInFromNothing(operation_2), run_time=0.7)\n        self.wait(3)\n        self.play(SpinInFromNothing(operation_3), run_time=0.7)\n        self.wait(4)\n        self.play(Group(*self.mobjects).animate.shift(9 * LEFT), run_time=0.5)\n        self.remove(*self.mobjects) </s>"}]}
{"messages": [{"role": "system", "content": "You are an expert Manim Community Edition (CE) programmer. Generate clean, executable Manim CE Python code that creates mathematical animations. Always use 'from manim import *' and ensure all code is compatible with the latest Manim CE version. Return ONLY the Python code, no explanations."}, {"role": "user", "content": "Could you create a vertical animation that shows all the unique ways to divide the number 10, displaying one-by-one, with the divisors and the results of each division getting larger, and then highlighting the divisors 1, 2, 5, and 10 with a red border before everything fades out? The background color should be customizable, and the animation should be suitable for a 1080x1920 portrait video format with the aspect ratio maintained at 9:16."}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "\\n from manim import *\n\nclass TripleIntegralExample(Scene):\n    def construct(self):\n        # Displaying the problem\n        problem = MathTex(r\"\\int_{0}^{1} \\int_{0}^{1} \\int_{0}^{1} xyz \\,dz\\,dy\\,dx\")\n        self.play(Write(problem))\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Explanation for inner integral\n        explanation1 = Text(\"First, integrate with respect to z\", font_size=24).to_edge(UP)\n        self.play(Write(explanation1))\n        self.wait(2)\n\n        # Inner integral step\n        inner_integral = MathTex(r\"= \\int_{0}^{1} \\int_{0}^{1} \\frac{1}{2}xy \\,dy\\,dx\")\n        self.play(ReplacementTransform(problem.copy(), inner_integral))\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Explanation for middle integral\n        explanation2 = Text(\"Next, integrate the result with respect to y\", font_size=24).to_edge(UP)\n        self.play(Transform(explanation1, explanation2))\n        self.wait(2)\n\n        # Middle integral step\n        middle_integral = MathTex(r\"= \\int_{0}^{1} \\frac{1}{4}x \\,dx\")\n        self.play(ReplacementTransform(inner_integral, middle_integral))\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Explanation for outer integral\n        explanation3 = Text(\"Finally, integrate the result with respect to x\", font_size=24).to_edge(UP)\n        self.play(Transform(explanation2, explanation3))\n        self.wait(2)\n\n        # Outer integral step and final solution\n        final_solution = MathTex(r\"= \\frac{1}{8}\")\n        self.play(ReplacementTransform(middle_integral, final_solution))\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Clear the scene and conclude\n        self.clear()\n        self.wait(1)\n        self.play(Write(final_solution))\n        self.wait(1)"}]}
{"messages": [{"role": "system", "content": "You are an expert Manim Community Edition (CE) programmer. Generate clean, executable Manim CE Python code that creates mathematical animations. Always use 'from manim import *' and ensure all code is compatible with the latest Manim CE version. Return ONLY the Python code, no explanations."}, {"role": "user", "content": "Generate accurate and correct ManimCE Python code for the animation requested by the user. Here is the user's request: Could you create an educational animation that introduces the wave equation from physics, explains its significance as a second-order linear partial differential equation (PDE), illustrates the general solution format, describes the meaning of the constant c in the equation, and concludes with the implications of initial conditions on the solution of the wave equation?"}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "\\n from manim import *\n\nclass AreaUnderCurveExample(Scene):\n    def construct(self):\n        # Define the area under the curve y=x^2 within the interval [0,3]\n        curve = FunctionGraph(lambda x: x**2, x_range=[0, 3], color=YELLOW)\n        area = area = Integral(curve, (x, 0, 3), fill_opacity=0.3, fill_color=BLUE)\n\n        # Display the curve\n        curve_label = MathTex(\"y = x^2\").next_to(curve, UP)\n        self.play(Create(curve), Write(curve_label))\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Show the area under the curve\n        self.play(Create(area))\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Problem statement\n        problem = MathTex(r\"\\int_0^3 x^2 \\,dx\")\n        problem.to_edge(UP + LEFT)   # Positioning the problem statement\n        self.play(Write(problem))\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Explanation of integration\n        explanation1 = Text(\"The area under the curve\", font_size=24).to_edge(UP)\n        self.play(Write(explanation1))\n        self.wait(2)\n\n        # Integration result before evaluation\n        integration_step = MathTex(r\"= \\left[\\frac{1}{3}x^3\\right]_0^3\")\n        self.play(ReplacementTransform(problem.copy(), integration_step))\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Evaluate at the bounds\n        explanation2 = Text(\"Evaluate at the bounds\", font_size=24).to_edge(UP)\n        self.play(Transform(explanation1, explanation2))\n        self.wait(2)\n\n        # Final result\n        final_solution = MathTex(r\"= \\frac{1}{3}(3)^3 - \\frac{1}{3}(0)^3\", r\"= 9\")\n        self.play(ReplacementTransform(integration_step, final_solution))\n        self.wait(2)\n\n        # Conclusion\n        self.clear()\n        conclusion = Text(\"The definite integral represents the area under the curve.\", font_size=24)\n        self.play(Write(conclusion))\n        self.wait(2) </s>"}]}
{"messages": [{"role": "system", "content": "You are an expert Manim Community Edition (CE) programmer. Generate clean, executable Manim CE Python code that creates mathematical animations. Always use 'from manim import *' and ensure all code is compatible with the latest Manim CE version. Return ONLY the Python code, no explanations."}, {"role": "user", "content": "Generate accurate and correct ManimCE Python code for the animation requested by the user. Here is the user's request: Can you create an educational animation using ManimCE that shows a 5 by 5 grid representing a simplified atomic structure, alternating between two elements like chlorine and sodium, with each atom represented by a colored circle and the element's symbol in the center? The chlorine atoms should have a green circle with 'Cl' in white text, and the sodium atoms should have an orange circle with 'Na' in white text. The animation should start by building up this grid of atoms and pause for a couple of seconds once complete so it's clear to viewers."}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "\\n from manim import *\n\nclass LinearWaveExampleScene(ThreeDScene):\n    def construct(self):\n        self.set_camera_orientation(60 * DEGREES, -45 * DEGREES)\n        wave = LinearWave()\n        self.add(wave)\n        wave.start_wave()\n        self.wait()\n        wave.stop_wave() </s>"}]}
{"messages": [{"role": "system", "content": "You are an expert Manim Community Edition (CE) programmer. Generate clean, executable Manim CE Python code that creates mathematical animations. Always use 'from manim import *' and ensure all code is compatible with the latest Manim CE version. Return ONLY the Python code, no explanations."}, {"role": "user", "content": "Create a circle with radius 1.5 and color it red."}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "from manim import * class MyScene(Scene): def construct(self): circle = Circle(radius=1.5, color=RED) self.add(circle)"}]}
{"messages": [{"role": "system", "content": "You are an expert Manim Community Edition (CE) programmer. Generate clean, executable Manim CE Python code that creates mathematical animations. Always use 'from manim import *' and ensure all code is compatible with the latest Manim CE version. Return ONLY the Python code, no explanations."}, {"role": "user", "content": "Can you create an educational animation that demonstrates how to calculate the area under the curve of x squared from x = 1 to x = 3, showing each step including the integral setup, applying the power rule of integration, and the final solution?"}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "\\n from manim import *\n\nclass ParametricCurve3D(ThreeDScene):\n    def construct(self):\n        curve = ParametricFunction(\n            lambda t: np.array([\n                np.sin(t), \n                np.cos(t), \n                t / 2\n            ]),\n            t_range=[0, TAU], \n            color=BLUE\n        )\n        axes = ThreeDAxes()\n\n        self.set_camera_orientation(phi=75 * DEGREES, theta=-45 * DEGREES)\n        self.play(Create(axes), Create(curve))\n        self.begin_ambient_camera_rotation(rate=0.1)\n        self.wait(5)"}]}
{"messages": [{"role": "system", "content": "You are an expert Manim Community Edition (CE) programmer. Generate clean, executable Manim CE Python code that creates mathematical animations. Always use 'from manim import *' and ensure all code is compatible with the latest Manim CE version. Return ONLY the Python code, no explanations."}, {"role": "user", "content": "Could you create an educational animation that introduces the concept of Fourier series, demonstrates the general formula for Fourier series, explains how it can represent periodic functions, gives a specific example of a Fourier series, and shows a graph of a simple function along with an explanation of applying Fourier series to a square wave function?"}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "\\n from manim import *\n\nclass AreaUnderCurve(Scene):\n    def construct(self):\n        axes = Axes(\n            x_range=[0, 4, 1],\n            y_range=[0, 4, 1],\n            axis_config={\"color\": BLUE},\n        )\n\n        # Create Graph\n        graph = axes.plot(lambda x: x**2, color=GREEN)\n\n        # Show area under curve\n        area = axes.get_area(graph, x_range=[0, 2])\n\n        curve_label = axes.get_graph_label(graph, label='y=x^2')\n\n        # Displaying the problem\n        problem = MathTex(r\"Area\\ under\\ y=x^2\\ from\\ x=0\\ to\\ x=2\")\n        problem.to_edge(UP)\n\n        self.play(Write(problem))\n        self.wait(1)\n        self.play(Create(axes), Create(graph))\n        self.play(FadeIn(area), Write(curve_label))\n        self.wait(2)\n\n        # Conclusion\n        conclusion = Text(\"Area is 8/3\", font_size=30).to_edge(DOWN)\n\n        self.play(ReplacementTransform(problem, conclusion))\n        self.wait(2)"}]}
{"messages": [{"role": "system", "content": "You are an expert Manim Community Edition (CE) programmer. Generate clean, executable Manim CE Python code that creates mathematical animations. Always use 'from manim import *' and ensure all code is compatible with the latest Manim CE version. Return ONLY the Python code, no explanations."}, {"role": "user", "content": "Generate accurate and correct ManimCE Python code for the animation requested by the user. Here is the user's request: I would like to create an animated video that explains the process of solving a differential equation. The specific equation I want to focus on is dy/dx = x^2 - y^2. I'd like the animation to proceed through the following steps: first, display the original equation, then show the process of separating variables, followed by integrating both sides of the equation, and finally, show the integrated result with the constant of integration. Each step should be written out mathematically, and I want a short pause after writing each step to give viewers time to comprehend the material."}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "\\n class Main(Scene):\n    def construct(self):\n            self.play(Transform(text,Text(\"CounterclockwiseTransform\").shift(UP*2.5)), run_time=0.5)\n            square = Square()\n            star = Star()\n            self.play(CounterclockwiseTransform(square,star))\n            self.remove(square,star) </s>"}]}
{"messages": [{"role": "system", "content": "You are an expert Manim Community Edition (CE) programmer. Generate clean, executable Manim CE Python code that creates mathematical animations. Always use 'from manim import *' and ensure all code is compatible with the latest Manim CE version. Return ONLY the Python code, no explanations."}, {"role": "user", "content": "I would like an animated video tutorial that visually demonstrates the process of solving a triple integral. Start by showing the integral of xyz over the unit cube from 0 to 1. Then, in step by step fashion, first integrate with respect to z while providing a text explanation above, next integrate the resulting expression with respect to y with new text explanation, and finally integrate with respect to x with another text explanation. At each step, the previous mathematical expression should transform into the new one. End the tutorial by clearing the screen and presenting the final solution of the integral."}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "\\n from manim import *\n\nclass BasicDefiniteIntegral(Scene):\n    def construct(self):\n        # Displaying the problem\n        problem = MathTex(r\"\\int_0^2 x^3 \\,dx\")\n        self.play(Write(problem))\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Explanation for the integration rule\n        explanation1 = Text(\"Using the power rule of integration:\", font_size=24).to_edge(UP)\n        self.play(Write(explanation1))\n        self.wait(2)\n\n        # Demonstrating the power rule\n        power_rule = MathTex(r\"\\int x^n \\,dx = \\frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1} + C\", r\" \\Bigg|_0^2\")\n        self.play(Write(power_rule))\n        self.wait(2)\n\n        # Performing the integration step\n        solution1 = MathTex(r\"= \\frac{x^{3+1}}{3+1}\", r\" \\Bigg|_0^2\")\n        self.play(ReplacementTransform(problem.copy(), solution1))\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Explanation for evaluating the definite integral\n        explanation2 = Text(\"Evaluating from 0 to 2\", font_size=24).to_edge(UP)\n        self.play(Transform(explanation1, explanation2))\n        self.wait(2)\n\n        # Final solution with bounds\n        integral_bound = MathTex(r\"= \\frac{x^4}{4} \\Bigg|_0^2\")\n        self.play(ReplacementTransform(solution1, integral_bound))\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Evaluating the bounds\n        solution = MathTex(r\"= \\frac{2^4}{4} - \\frac{0^4}{4}\")\n        self.play(ReplacementTransform(integral_bound, solution))\n        self.wait(2)\n\n        # Final solution\n        final_solution = MathTex(r\"= \\frac{16}{4} - 0\", \"=\", \"4\")\n        self.play(ReplacementTransform(solution, final_solution))\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Clear the scene\n        self.clear()\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Conclude with the final solution\n        self.play(Write(final_solution))\n        self.wait(1)"}]}
{"messages": [{"role": "system", "content": "You are an expert Manim Community Edition (CE) programmer. Generate clean, executable Manim CE Python code that creates mathematical animations. Always use 'from manim import *' and ensure all code is compatible with the latest Manim CE version. Return ONLY the Python code, no explanations."}, {"role": "user", "content": "Generate accurate and correct ManimCE Python code for the animation requested by the user. Here is the user's request: I would like to create an educational video that explains how to find the area under a curve using integration. Can you show me a visual animation where it starts by displaying a mathematical function, specifically f(x) = 3x^2 + 2, and poses an initial problem: finding the area under this curve from x = 1 to x = 2? After establishing this problem, I want the animation to graph the function on an x-y plane with axes ranging from 0 to 3 on the x-axis and 0 to 20 on the y-axis. I would also like the area of interest under the curve to be highlighted. Once the problem is visually represented, can the animation then show the integral of the function from 1 to 2, and the steps to solve it, eventually displaying the antiderivative and calculating the numerical area value? Finally, clear everything away and show only the final result of the area value. The explanation should pause at key steps to give viewers time to understand the process, and each part of the problem should smoothly transition into the next."}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "\\n from manim import *\n\nclass BasicDefiniteIntegral(Scene):\n    def construct(self):\n        # Displaying the problem\n        problem = MathTex(r\"\\int_2^3 x^3 \\,dx\")\n        self.play(Write(problem))\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Explanation for the integration rule\n        explanation1 = Text(\"Using the power rule of integration:\", font_size=24).to_edge(UP)\n        self.play(Write(explanation1))\n        self.wait(2)\n\n        # Demonstrating the power rule\n        power_rule = MathTex(r\"\\int x^n \\,dx = \\frac{x^{n+1}}{n+1} + C\")\n        self.play(Write(power_rule))\n        self.wait(2)\n\n        # Display the limits of integration\n        limits = MathTex(r\"[2^4/4, 3^4/4]\")\n        self.play(Write(limits))\n        self.wait(2)\n\n        # Evaluating the definite integral\n        solution1 = MathTex(r\"= \\frac{3^4}{4} - \\frac{2^4}{4}\")\n        self.play(ReplacementTransform(problem.copy(), solution1))\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Simplifying the result\n        explanation2 = Text(\"Simplifying the result:\", font_size=24).to_edge(UP)\n        self.play(Transform(explanation1, explanation2))\n        self.wait(2)\n\n        # Final solution\n        final_solution = MathTex(r\"= \\frac{81}{4} - \\frac{16}{4}\")\n        self.play(ReplacementTransform(solution1, final_solution))\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Further simplification\n        final_answer = MathTex(r\"= \\frac{65}{4}\")\n        self.play(ReplacementTransform(final_solution, final_answer))\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Clear the scene\n        self.clear()\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Conclude with the final answer\n        self.play(Write(final_answer))\n        self.wait(1) </s>"}]}
{"messages": [{"role": "system", "content": "You are an expert Manim Community Edition (CE) programmer. Generate clean, executable Manim CE Python code that creates mathematical animations. Always use 'from manim import *' and ensure all code is compatible with the latest Manim CE version. Return ONLY the Python code, no explanations."}, {"role": "user", "content": "Scale the triangle by a factor of 0.5 in 1 second."}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "from manim import * class MyScene(Scene): def construct(self): triangle = RegularPolygon(n=3, radius=3, color=PINK) self.add(triangle) self.play(triangle.animate.scale(0.5), run_time=1)"}]}
{"messages": [{"role": "system", "content": "You are an expert Manim Community Edition (CE) programmer. Generate clean, executable Manim CE Python code that creates mathematical animations. Always use 'from manim import *' and ensure all code is compatible with the latest Manim CE version. Return ONLY the Python code, no explanations."}, {"role": "user", "content": "Generate accurate and correct ManimCE Python code for the animation requested by the user. Here is the user's request: Could you create an animated visualization of a variational autoencoder neural network architecture using images as input and output with a code snippet overlay that explains how the network is constructed?"}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "\\n from manim import *\n\nclass Custom2DGridScene(Scene):\n    def create_grid(self, rows: int, cols: int, cell_size: float = 1.0):\n        \"\"\"\n        Create a 2D grid of squares given row and column counts.\n\n        Args:\n            rows (int): The number of rows in the grid.\n            cols (int): The number of columns in the grid.\n            cell_size (float): The side length of each square cell.\n\n        Returns:\n            VGroup: A group containing all the grid squares.\n        \"\"\"\n        grid = VGroup()\n        for i in range(rows):\n            for j in range(cols):\n                square = Square(side_length=cell_size)\n                square.move_to(np.array([j * cell_size, -i * cell_size, 0]))\n                grid.add(square)\n        grid.move_to(ORIGIN)  # Center the grid.\n        return grid\n\n    def construct(self):\n        rows, cols = 5, 5  # Define the number of rows and columns for the grid.\n        grid = self.create_grid(rows, cols)  # Create the grid using the helper function.\n        self.add(grid)  # Add the grid to the scene.\n\nclass ComplexPathAnimation(Scene):\n    def construct(self):\n        # Create a dot that will move along a path.\n        dot = Dot(radius=0.1, color=RED)\n        \n        # Define the complex path points.\n        path_points = [UP * 2, UP + RIGHT * 2, DOWN + RIGHT * 2, DOWN * 2, DOWN + LEFT * 2, UP + LEFT * 2, UP * 2]\n        complex_path = VGroup()\n        \n        # Iterate over the points to create the visual path with lines.\n        for i in range(len(path_points) - 1):\n            line = Line(path_points[i], path_points[i + 1], stroke_width=2, color=BLUE)\n            complex_path.add(line)\n        \n        # Show the path on screen.\n        self.add(complex_path)\n        \n        # Create a custom animation by moving the dot along the defined path.\n        def custom_path_position(alpha):\n            num_points = len(path_points)\n            curr_point = int(alpha * (num_points - 1))\n            sub_alpha = (alpha * (num_points - 1)) % 1\n            return path_points[curr_point] + (path_points[curr_point + 1] - path_points[curr_point]) * sub_alpha\n\n        self.play(MoveAlongPath(dot, complex_path), run_time=4, rate_func=linear)\n        self.add(dot)  # Keep the dot displayed at the end. </s>"}]}
{"messages": [{"role": "system", "content": "You are an expert Manim Community Edition (CE) programmer. Generate clean, executable Manim CE Python code that creates mathematical animations. Always use 'from manim import *' and ensure all code is compatible with the latest Manim CE version. Return ONLY the Python code, no explanations."}, {"role": "user", "content": "Generate accurate and correct ManimCE Python code for the animation requested by the user. Here is the user's request: I would like to create an animated video that demonstrates different concepts in chemistry, starting with the formation of a simple molecule. The video should show the individual atoms or particles coming together to form a molecule, followed by the transformation of this molecule into a metal oxide grid. Afterward, I'd like to see this grid change into a carbon grid structure. Both grid transformations should be smoothly animated. Finally, the animation should show an electron moving in a complex path around the molecule or grid, mimicking the motion of electrons in an atomic structure. The entire sequence should be visually engaging and help illustrate the dynamic nature of chemical structures. Can you create such an animation for me?"}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "\\n from manim import *\n\nclass HarmonicSeriesConvergence(Scene):\n    def construct(self):\n        # Introducing the Harmonic series\n        harmonic_series = MathTex(r\"\\sum_{n=1}^{\\infty} \\frac{1}{n}\")\n        self.play(Write(harmonic_series))\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Discuss convergence\n        convergence_text = Text(\"Does this series converge?\", font_size=24).to_edge(UP)\n        self.play(Write(convergence_text))\n        self.wait(2)\n\n        # Applying the integral test\n        integral_test = MathTex(r\"\\int_1^\\infty \\frac{1}{x} \\,dx\")\n        self.play(Transform(harmonic_series, integral_test))\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Display divergence explanation\n        divergence_explanation = Text(\"This improper integral diverges\", font_size=24).to_edge(UP)\n        self.play(Transform(convergence_text, divergence_explanation))\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Writing the steps for the integral test result\n        integral_steps = MathTex(r\"\\lim_{b \\to \\infty} \\ln{|x|}_1^b\")\n        self.play(ReplacementTransform(integral_test, integral_steps))\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Conclude with divergence of the series\n        divergent_result = MathTex(r\"\\sum_{n=1}^{\\infty} \\frac{1}{n}\", r\"\\text{ diverges}\")\n        self.play(ReplacementTransform(integral_steps, divergent_result))\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Clear the scene\n        self.clear()\n        self.wait(1)\n\n        # Reaffirm the result\n        reaffirm_conclusion = Text(\"The harmonic series diverges.\", font_size=24)\n        self.play(Write(reaffirm_conclusion))\n        self.wait(1) </s>"}]}
{"messages": [{"role": "system", "content": "You are an expert Manim Community Edition (CE) programmer. Generate clean, executable Manim CE Python code that creates mathematical animations. Always use 'from manim import *' and ensure all code is compatible with the latest Manim CE version. Return ONLY the Python code, no explanations."}, {"role": "user", "content": "Can you create an animated video that explains how to calculate the area under the curve for the function x squared between the values x equals 1 and x equals 3, including a step-by-step demonstration of evaluating the definite integral, and showing the final result?"}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "\\n from manim import *\n\nclass WaveEquationExample(Scene):\n    def construct(self):\n        # Showing the wave equation\n        wave_eq = MathTex(r\"\\frac{\\partial^2 u}{\\partial t^2} = c^2 \\frac{\\partial^2 u}{\\partial x^2}\")\n        self.play(FadeIn(wave_eq))\n        self.wait(2)\n\n        # Displaying solution form\n        solution_form = Text(\"Solutions can be of the form u(x, t) = f(x \\pm ct)\", font_size=24).to_edge(DOWN)\n        self.play(Write(solution_form))\n        self.wait(3)\n\n        # Displaying a specific solution\n        specific_solution = MathTex(r\"u(x, t) = A \\sin(kx - \\omega t)\")\n        self.play(ReplacementTransform(wave_eq, specific_solution))\n        self.wait(2)\n\n        # Explaining the parameters\n        parameters_explanation = Text(\"Here, A is amplitude, k is the wave number, and ω is the angular frequency\", font_size=24).to_edge(DOWN)\n        self.play(Transform(solution_form, parameters_explanation))\n        self.wait(3)\n\n        # Show boundary conditions\n        boundary_conditions = MathTex(r\"u(0, t) = u(L, t) = 0\")\n        self.play(FadeIn(boundary_conditions), FadeOut(specific_solution), FadeOut(solution_form))\n        self.wait(3)\n\n        # Clear the scene and show a conclusion\n        self.clear()\n        self.wait(1)\n        conclusion = Text(\"Wave equations model vibrations and waves.\", font_size=24).to_edge(UP)\n        self.play(Write(conclusion))\n        self.wait(1)\n        self.play(FadeOut(conclusion))"}]}
{"messages": [{"role": "system", "content": "You are an expert Manim Community Edition (CE) programmer. Generate clean, executable Manim CE Python code that creates mathematical animations. Always use 'from manim import *' and ensure all code is compatible with the latest Manim CE version. Return ONLY the Python code, no explanations."}, {"role": "user", "content": "Could you create an animated video that demonstrates a Hamiltonian cycle on a graph with 20 nodes? I'd like to show the nodes as dots and connect them with lines to illustrate the cycle. The dots should form concentric circles and be color-coded as they are visited in the cycle. Once the cycle is complete, I want the entire graph to move to the left side of the screen and have text appear that says \"The graph\" alongside a miniature version of the graph, followed by another text line underneath it that states \"has a Hamiltonian cycle.\" Then, end the video by fading everything out."}, {"role": "assistant", "content": "\\n from manim import *\n\nclass DisplayUnits(Scene):\n    def construct(self):\n        # Create a grid to visualize screen units\n        grid = NumberPlane()\n        self.add(grid)\n\n        # Different percentages of the screen width and color for each rectangle\n        percentages = [10, 20, 30, 40, 50]\n        colors = [RED, GREEN, BLUE, ORANGE, PURPLE]\n\n        # Create and add rectangles to the scene\n        for percent, color in zip(percentages, colors):\n            self.add(\n                Rectangle(\n                    width=percent * Percent(X_AXIS),\n                    height=10 * Percent(Y_AXIS),\n                    color=color,\n                    fill_opacity=0.5\n                )\n            )\n\n        # Create and add a dot at a fixed number of pixels from the origin\n        dot = Dot(point=ORIGIN).shift(150 * Pixels * UP + 150 * Pixels * RIGHT)\n        self.add(dot)"}]}
